column168: RESPONDED TO A PACKAGE THAT NEEDED TO BE REWRAPPED. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS DISCOVERED ONE HQRP NI-MH BATTERY THAT APPEARED BLACKENED AND CORRODED AT THE TERMINALS. THE BATTERY WAS PACKAGED IN AN OUTER PLASTIC AMAZON POLYMAILER BAG. THE NI-MH BATTERY WAS ENCLOSED IN A CLEAR PLASTIC BAG INSIDE THE POLYMAILER BAG. NO ADDITIONAL INNER PACKAGING. THE THERMAL LABEL IS MARKED "NOT RESTRICTED AS PER SPECIAL PROVISION A199". HOWEVER, THE BATTERY HAS NOT BEEN PREPARED OR PACKAGED IN A MANNER TO PREVENT SHORT CIRCUIT OR DAMAGE TO THE TERMINALS PER SPECIAL PROVISION A199. NO EXTERNAL RELEASE INTO THE ENVIRONMENT. REPORTING PER 171.16. PRIOR TO DISCOVERY, THE PACKAGE WAS GROUND FED FROM MICHIGAN TO THE DISCOVERY FACILITY IN LOUISVILLE KENTUCKY. THE PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED USING UPS ACCOUNT NUMBER W612R6, AMAZON.COM.KYDC, INC., 1200 FEATHERSTONE RD., PONTIAC MI 48342. THIS PACKAGE HAS NOT BEEN ACCEPTED FOR AIR OR TRANSPORTED IN THE AIR BY UNITED PARCEL SERVICE, CO.

When the driver went to pick up the loaded trailer that was staged at the Quala tankwash, he observed some product on the outside of the trailer.  Nothing appeared to have impacted the ground around the trailer.  This trailer has a rubber lining on it.  He tightened the lugs down more than usual which stopped the leak in transit.  However this is usually an indicator that the lining around the collar where the dome lid comes down is having an issue where the rubber doesn't make perfect surface contact that will need to be repaired.  Trailer is out of service pending repairs.
column169: We have imposed a self inspection interval of every 4 months to try and catch common issues before they become a problem in transit.  However this is not something we are seeing as a trend or routine issue and at this time appears to be an isolated event.  We will continue to monitor these trailers going forward.

column168: On 10/10/202, BNSF SSeattle IMF notified LARS of destination unit JBHU 239342 (billed HAZ, UN 1263, Flammable Paint) which was observed to be leaking a liquid during the de   ramping process. Upon inspection US Ecology observed a standard shipment with multiple differentiating pieces of cargo unsecured on pallets and no void fillers. During transit the pallets were able to shift and puncture 3     6.5   gallon cans that caused the total leakage of 10.5 gallons of paint related material, confirmed to be hazardous, UN 1263. USE completed the remediation by securing the remaining buckets and re    palletized, and all three damaged buckets were secured in containers to prevent any additional leakage.
column169: Ensure proper securement of hazardous packages when loading.

column168: CTCX 733536 identified by Mechanical as releasing from top of car.  Upon inspection, the liquid line was slightly open with a loose liquid line plug.  The liquid line was closed and plug secured.  Contractor was mobilized to decontaminate exterior and due to no active release from liquid line, a secondary release from vacuum relief valve was identified due to increasing pressure from initial securement.  VRV was removed and replaced with plug and OTMA applied to continue movement.

All UN1805-impacted material was collected in eleven (11) 55-gallon drums.

On October 7, 2022, one (1) 5-gallon pail of BIOTROL 355 was damaged due to a load shift and released approximately three (3) ounces of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC, who dispatched a crew from WRR Environmental Services (WRR) to perform the necessary corrective actions. WRR personnel utilized absorbents and hand tools to remediate the impacted surface, then containerized all BIOTROL 355-impacted material into one (1) 5-gallon container for disposal.

SequenceEvent: Package had molded cardboard underneath all four bottles, but the top piece of molded cardboard was not in the package, nor were there partitions between the bottles, allowing the bottles to move around inside the box. When the package was discovered during unload, the event had already occurred and the box was dry. The sound of broken glass was detected. The package was placed in a lined bin and brought to QA where it was processed as damaged. DescribePack: The upper piece of molded cardboard, which was present in several of the other boxes also containing methanol, was not inside the box when it was opened. Nor were there partitions of any kind between the bottles. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Since the event occurred during transit, and by the time it was discovered, the box was dry, there were no actions taken that i know of, other than collecting all the broken bottle pieces and including them in the damage bin.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: SequenceEvent: I was assisting my qa team today and when I came to belt 3 it was sitting on a pallet near the QA computer station. I noticed it was paint materials and immediately put it in a lined bin at around 7:30am. DescribePack: Upon discovery of the package there was a distinct odor and the package itself was wet on the top of the box and some of the side and bottom. The tape that sealed it wasn't an issue to which I will elude to later. I found the contents of the package to be boat paint sealer and the cap clips that would usually hold a can of paint's cover in place were in an upward position. Unsure of how they up like that but as a result the covers on both cans of paint were slightly popped open enough for a few ounces to come out. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Initially I grabbed a surgical mask and double gloved before going anywhere near the package and then put the damaged package into a lined black bin just in case the leaking hadn't subsided and then checked to make sure the cans were facing up as well.

SequenceEvent: Appears cap was loose or not properly sealed and liquid contents leaked. DescribePack: Top of jerrican/jug at cap closure. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Fiberboard box was placed in salvage tub and removed from sort , taken to HazMat secured cage area.

SequenceEvent: On October 7, 2022 at 1630 hours, I was informed by my supervisor to process a damaged hazmat package that the previous shift had placed in the East HazMat cage. I found the damaged Hazmat inside a blue plastic bag that was inside an orange plastic container. Upon opening the plastic bag, I found a white package that had wet spots. No other damage was observed on package. Pictures were taken of package and of all its contents. Package contained four, 1-gallon plastic containers each filled with Master Care Triple D Medium Duty Universal Coil Cleaner. One of the containers had a loose cap and an open seal. This allowed about 5 ounces of its contents to spill inside package. Upon inspection of package, I found that the Tracking # on label (6093 3554 7638) did not match the Tracking # on the OP-900 (6093 3554 7660). However, the hazmat description and quantity on the OP-900 did match the information listed on the package. I also discovered that the hazmat package did not have the required, 4 inch per side, colored, Corrosive hazard label.  This package did not have the Hazmat certificate since it was processed on 10-05-22, at 310 BRSL. DescribePack: The outer package did not have any visible damage except for some wet spots caused by the spilled hazmat. The failure was the result of one container having a loose cap and an open seal. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The damaged hazmat package was immediately placed in a blue plastic bag and the bag opening was tied closed. The plastic bag was then placed in an orange plastic container. The orange container was then placed in the secure East HazMat cage.

SequenceEvent: Package arrived at our facility already damaged. The package was knocked off the pallet and overturned with a mass amount of the corrosive material around the trailer. Proper PPE and safety hazmat equipment was used to clean up the corrosive spill and the damage was placed in salvage drum. DescribePack: Upon inspection of damage, two caps were completely off the bottles and the other two bottles were dented and leaking as well. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: Proper PPE and safety hazmat equipment was used to clean up the corrosive spill and the damage was placed in salvage drum. The trailer was then sent to the yard with door open to air out fumes and to let it properly dry before the trailer was safe enough to continue to be unloaded.

column168: At 0919 ET, XPO terminal NMP contacted ERTS to report a spill that occurred inside a trailer at 0900 ET in Memphis, TN. The spill consisted of a 55 gallon poly drum containingUN1760 "WinKlean 4500", which arrived at the terminal in a damaged condition, likely due to it falling off of the pallet during transit, causing a small pin-sized hole which released approximately 2 cups onto the floor of the trailer and on the pallet. ERTS dispatched E3 to conduct cleanup operations. At 1325 ET, E3 personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 25 gallons of product released to a 15' x 3" area of the trailer and a 10' x 20' area of the concrete lot below the trailer. The damaged drum was containerized into an 85 gallon metal drum. Absorbents were then worked into the impacted areas and collected into (2) 55 gallon poly drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: XPO terminal NAT reported a release of 42 gallons of "PureSolv Isopropyl Alcohol" (UN1219) after a pallet punctured a 42-gallon poly drum during dock operations. ERTS dispatched Miller Environmental to conduct cleanup. At 0625 ET, Miller personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 42-gallons of product released to a 6' x 6' area of the dock floor due to a pallet puncturing the drum. The damaged drum was placed into a 95 gallon poly overpack. Absorbents were then worked into the impacted areas, collected, and containerized into (3) 55 gallon poly drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

At 0455 ET, XPO reported a pallet of UN3266 ZEP MORADO SUPER CLEANER had been tipped over in a trailer. At least 5 gallons of product had been spilled. ERTS dispatched Patriot to conduct cleanup. At 0700 ET, Patriot arrived on-site at and observed a toppled pallet of 5-gallon pails containing Zep Morado Super Cleaner with at least one pail leaking from the lid. Patriot secured the leaking pail and re-stacked the remaining pails. Crew confirmed 2 gallons released to a 4' x 6' area of the trailer floor. Absorbents were worked into the impacted area and then collected along with the damaged pail into a 55 gallon poly drum. Three additional pails were found damaged but not releasing, these were placed into a separate 55 gallon poly drum. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: Highway Transport (HT) driver loaded at the shipper and was released once the trailer was loaded. This was a Shipper load, no assistance from the driver. HT driver signed for paperwork, weighed out and left the shipper. Approximately two miles down the road a motorist informed HT driver that the trailer was leaking. HT driver drove approximately one to two miles further before looking for a safe place to pull over and check the trailer. Once stopped, HT driver confirmed that the trailer was leaking and contacted the Service Center Manager in Pittsburg, PA. Emergency crews were called out and the area surrounding the tractor and trailer were secured. HT dispatched Hill International to come out and repair the trailer. This is when it was determined that the dome lid was leaking on the trailer. Mechanic reported to HT that the dome lid was not secured (wing nuts loose) and that he was going to secure the dome lid. After doing so, the driver was released to continue to our Pittsburg, PA Service Center. After arriving to our Service Center, it was discovered that the trailer continued to leak. The mechanic from the same the company was dispatched to our Service Center for a more detailed inspection of the trailer. This is when it was discovered that the dome lid was missing the gasket and that is what contributed to the spill. Once the dome lid gasket was installed, then we tested the trailer by performing numerous bump test, and no more leaks was discovered. Trailer was released and driver made delivery without any more problems.
column169: HT driver was coached and assigned additional training for load securement, reporting procedures, and driver responsibility.

column168: Highway Transport (HT) driver loaded at the shipper and was released once the trailer was loaded. This was a Shipper load, no assistance from the driver. HT driver signed for paperwork, weighed out and left the shipper. Approximately two miles down the road a motorist informed HT driver that the trailer was leaking. HT driver drove approximately one to two miles further before looking for a safe place to pull over and check the trailer. Once stopped, HT driver confirmed that the trailer was leaking and contacted the Service Center Manager in Pittsburg, PA. Emergency crews were called out and the area surrounding the tractor and trailer were secured. HT dispatched Hill International to come out and repair the trailer. This is when it was determined that the dome lid was leaking on the trailer. Mechanic reported to HT that the dome lid was not secured (wing nuts loose) and that he was going to secure the dome lid. After doing so, the driver was released to continue to our Pittsburg, PA Service Center. After arriving to our Service Center, it was discovered that the trailer continued to leak. The mechanic from the same the company was dispatched to our Service Center for a more detailed inspection of the trailer. This is when it was discovered that the dome lid was missing the gasket and that is what contributed to the spill. Once the dome lid gasket was installed, then we tested the trailer by performing numerous bump test, and no more leaks was discovered. Trailer was released and driver made delivery without any more problems.
column169: HT driver was coached and assigned additional training for load securement, reporting procedures, and driver responsibility.

column168: When the Rook Yard Conductor was walking his train, he noticed tank car PROX 43540 leaking from the manway lid.  They contacted the WLE Rook yard Yardmaster who then contacted myself, John Vergis Hazardous Materials Officer for WLE.  I then called Specialized Professional Services our of Washington, PA to go to the yard and look at the car.  When they investigated, they found that the manway bolts were not tightened properly which allowed for the leak. They opened the manway and inspected the gasket which appeared to be in good shape.  They then closed the lid and properly tightened and installed new seal and wiped down the side of the car.  The car was then released for transportation.

column168: When a WLE train crew at the WLE Rook Yard was passing through the yard, they noticed an odor coming from Tank Car PROX 45361.  When they investigated, they could hear a hissing coming from the top of the car.  They notified the WLE Yardmaster who then called myself, John Vergis, Hazardous Materials Officer for the WLE.  I called Specialized Professional Services out of Washington, PA to go out and investigate.  When they arrived, they found that the Vacuum Relief Device was failed and allowing the car to exhaust fumes. PACKAGE WAS BROGUHT BACK ONCE THE AREA WAS SWEPT FREE OF DEBRIS. THE PACKAGE WAS IMMEDIATELY PROCESSED USING THE WASTE DISPOSAL FOR A FULL DMP FLOW CHART. column168: On 10/28/2022, at 1714, personnel in the CSXT South Charleston Yard discovered GCCX 81058, a loaded Covered Hopper car of Ammonium Nitrate, leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and shipper, the National Response Center, and Chemtrec were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2022-1028-00242). Quick Response, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found an unsecure gate door at the bottom of the chute. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Pete Rucks with CF Industries 847-436-6711. Contractor personnel secured the gate door, collected and containerized any released material, and decontaminated the impacted area. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 not required.  Cause Code:662 NARRI:130

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: On October 19, 2022, the Veolia driver and technician arrived at the generator's site around 8am and started to offload supplies and prepare for the waste containers to be loaded on to the truck. Once they finished offloading the supplies, a third Veolia employee operating a forklift began loading five 85 gal 1H2 poly salvage drums onto the truck. Each 85 gallon salvage drum contained a compromised 55 gallon 1H1 drum containing 96% sulfuric acid. The forklift operator placed the drums on the tail end of the straight truck and the two Veolia personnel utilized a pallet jack to move the drums to the nose of the straight truck. When they went to get the the fifth drum, they noticed the 4th drum started to bulge on top. Shortly after, they noticed a mist was visible near the drum and the employees immediately exited out of the box of the straight truck. The Veolia employees observed the drum from outside of the truck and could see it was increasing in pressure and bulging. The drum eventually ruptured due to the pressure and started to release the liquid and absorbent that was placed inside the salvage drum. The total duration of the reaction and release was roughly 30 minutes and the estimated quantity of hazardous material that spilled out of the package was roughly 2 gallons.   The Veolia employees contained the spill by laying down visqueen and spill pads under the truck due to the sulfuric acid leaking through the floorboards onto the ground. They donned level B PPE and re-containerized the drum. This drum was left on the generator's site and was not shipped. Veolia employees completed the spill response and neutralized the acid that had leaked out.
column169: After reviewing the incident, it was determined that during the salvage packaging operation, diatomaceous earth was not used but rather organic based (paper) absorbent was utilized. High concentration sulfuric acid acts like a oxidizer and likely contributed to the reaction.  In addition, it had rained two days earlier and likely humidity exacerbated the process due to water being absorbed by the organic based absorbent.   Veolia will train employees to make sure they understand the characteristics of absorbent that is being utilized. In addition, prior to purchase, Veolia will confirm that diatomaceous earth is purchased and not the paper product absorbent that was received due to the paper product resembling diatomaceous earth and can easily be confused.

On October 31, 2022, one (1) 55-gallon drum containing potassium hydroxide (UN3266) toppled during unloading and released approximately 0.5 gallon of product to the trailer floor and concrete beneath. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC, who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to complete the necessary corrective actions. FCE personnel utilized absorbents and hand tools to remediate the impacted surface, then containerized all potassium hydroxide-impacted material and the damaged drum in three (3) 55-gallon drums and one (1) 95-gallon overpack for transport and disposal.

The KA Bulk Transport, LLC driver was loading the trailer with crude coal tar. A discharge valve on the trailer failed and allowed approximately 9100 pounds of crude coal tar to be released. The spilled product was isolated in the shipper's containment area. The shipper had personnel respond and remediate the spill.
column169: KA Bulk Transport, LLC will make the necessary repairs to the trailer in order to avoid a recurrence.

column168: On October 23, 2022 at approximately 08:30 CDT during an inspection of tank car PROX 43062, Load, Styrene Monomer, Stabilized, UN 2055, Class 3, PG III, at the CN Kirk Yard, Gary, IN., a CN Mechanical crew observed liquid dripping from the bottom outlet area. The railcar was isolated, all required notifications made. CN Response team responded and upon closer inspection observed a small leak emanating from the bottom outlet valve flange area. The bolts were checked for tightness, and one was able to be tightened 1/2 turn and an adjacent bolt was tightened 1/4 turn, securing the leak. The area and the exterior surface of the tank car was decontaminated and observed for 30 minutes.

At 0240 ET, FCE personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 5 gallons of UN1866 "Derakane Signia 411 Epoxy" released from a 55 gallon metal drum due to a puncture. column168: On 10/22/2022, at 1013 hours, personnel in the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered UTLX 206614, a loaded tank car of Fuel Oil, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper of record, National Response Center, and New York Department of Environmental Conservation were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2022-1022-00112). Marion Environmental, Inc, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found multiple manway cover bolts less than tool tight, resulting in a release of lading. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper of record, it was determined the offeror of the car was Petroleum Services Corporation, phone 412.420.4076. Contractor personnel secured all manway cover bolts in accordance with 49 CFR 173.31 and cleaned all impacted car surfaces. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required. column168: On October 17, 2022, at 00:30 hours, Transportation reported that at the Conrail North Yard, Detroit Michigan reported that GATX 90905, a loaded tank car of UN 1778, Fluorsilicic Acid had leaked upon normal switching operations.. Reportedly product blew out of the top valves on the tank car. The tank car was isolated from the crews and employees in the yard. The shipper, JR Simplot, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2022-10-17-00254. Enviroserve, a Conrail emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the North Yard. Enviroserve found that the rupture disk had blown out thus causing the release. After further inspection the tank car was equiped with a salco rupture disk component and found that surge protection was not in place. Additionally the plasteic inspection cap was broken. The shipper representative, Justin Akin, 313-626-2422 was notified of the situation found. Jr Simplot had Rescar replace the Salco rupture disk component and filed One Time Movement Approval #FRA-221110004.  This incident did require a special move. The 4.1 classification was used as a place holder tp ensure 5800 submission**   On 10/18/2022, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from DG Spill Office, reporting a package fire in the Secondary in International sort area.   At approximately 0958, the package appeared to have ignited, resulting in a fire and causing damage to several other packages. The Hub Fire Department was called to the scene to extinguish the flame and neutralize the package. Per Captain Easton, the initial shipment appeared to have been tendered via US Postal Service and emitted an odor similar to paint thinner. Postal Transportation has taken possession of the initial package and the additional damaged packages.  The National Response Center has been notified and a report has been filed under Report # 1350266 by Mr. Threatt.  The Federal Aviation Administration has also been made aware of the incident.

column168: XPO Terminal XCF contacted ERTS to report a one-cup spill of regulated UN2796 "Sulfuric Acid 50%" (sulfuric acid, with not more than 51% acid) that was released inside trailer #4635376 due to the drums not being properly sealed. ERTS dispatched contractors to assess. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-quart of product released to a 2' x 2' area of the trailer floor. DescribePack: The paint cans was possibly damaged due to incorrect stacking on the trailer which caused the paint can lids to be bent and then the paint spilled inside. The paint got on multiple boxes outside of its own. The paint cans was packed with just some inner corrugated liners inside, the corrugated liners are connected to the box when you open it up. column168: 1. X-2022110554 SequenceEvent: A QA member found the package at the chute area and notified me that it was some paint. I dropped what I was doing and headed to the chute. DescribePack: The Paint cans was found with one paint can lid bent and spilled all over the other cans. The package itself was possibly not stacked correctly in the trailer causing the damage. The small hole on the lid was enough to spill out a lot of it. There was no D.O.T label on the side of the box, the symbol where the D.O.T was suppose to be wasn't there. DurationRel: 5 and MitigateEffect: I removed the package from the chute and thankfully there was no paint on the chute.   2. X-2022110555 SequenceEvent: Management notified QA that there was three boxes had yellow paint on them. QA rushed to unload to check for the packages. The damaged paint box was found in the trailer, damaged. QA immediately got to repacking on the packages that was wet from the paint and then process the actual paint package. DescribePack: The paint cans was possibly damaged due to incorrect stacking on the trailer which caused the paint can lids to be bent and then the paint spilled inside. The paint got on multiple boxes outside of its own. The paint cans was packed with just some inner corrugated liners inside, the corrugated liners are connected to the box when you open it up. That was the only inner packing inside. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: The wet packages from the paint was removed from trailer and placed on pallet so QA can process and repacked immediately.

SequenceEvent: The package was brought to QA at unload by a package handler. The package was wet on its side and the QA from called on the authorized QA for HazMat. They said they were okay. DescribePack: The canisters for the denatured alcohol was found with one out six damaged. The top of the lid where the cap was, it was shown to be bent which caused the cap to be loose and caused the leakage. There was no inner packing for the canisters inside the package, they all fitted in the box, but the box could've used some inner packing to keep the canisters from getting damaged. column168: On October 25, 2022 at 0818, personnel in the CSXT QueensGate Yard discovered GATX 24969, a residue tank car of Sodium Methylate, leaking from the Vacuum Relief Valve (VRV) on top of the car. The car was isolated and The Louis Dreyfus Company, the National Response Center, and CHEMTREC were notified. CHEMTREC Report #2022-10-26-00219. EnviroServe, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and located GATX24969 with the leaking VRV. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Janelle Sexter 888-381-0760. Contractor personnel cleaned the Sodium Methylate residue from the tank car decontaminating this area on top of the car. The leak was secured and Home Shop Do Not Load decals were affixed to both sides of the car. This incident did not require a special switching move.  7.1 not required.  Cause Code:100 NARRI:200

column168: On 10/26/2022, at 1436 hours, personnel in the CSXT Connellsville Yard discovered UTLX 647538, a loaded tank car of Acrylic Acid, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Protection were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2022-1026-00230). Specialized Professional Services, Inc, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found an active leak from the liquid valve packing gland nut. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Mr. Wayne Meadows, phone 832-205-6586. Contractor personnel tightened the packing gland nut and secured the observed release. Due to weather conditions personnel were unable to confirm if the liquid valve packing gland was the only point of release, and contractor personnel returned the next day, applied 4-5 psi of air to the service equipment and observed a defective liquid valve leaking in the closed position. As of this 5800.1 report, the car remains on hold pending replacement of the defective component. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is required.  Cause Code: 296 NARRI:40

ON 10/15 AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 THE STATION AT MRIA CONTACTED DG ADMIN ABOUT A LEAKING PACKAGE FOUND DURING THE MORNING SORT. THERE WERE NO INDICATIONS ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE THAT THIS WAS A DANGEROUS GOOD OR ANY SHIPPERS DECLARATION OF DANGEROUS GOODS. ONE OF THE HANDLERS BROUGHT IT TO THE CSAS FOR REPACKING. AN EMPLOYEE BEGAN TO DO THE REWRAP AND GOT SOME OF THE GEL ON THEIR HANDS. ONCE IT WAS DETERMINED THAT IT WAS A DANGEROUS GOOD, AFTER REVIEWING THE SAFETY DATA SHEET, THEY STOPPED AND WASHED THEIR HANDS THOROUGHLY. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS REQUIRED. EMPLOYEE SHOWS NO SIGNS OF AFTER EFFECTS. TWO BOTTLES IN THE PACKAGE HAD LOOSE CAPS AND HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 0.5L COMBINED. THE INSIDE OF THE BOX SHOWED EXTREME SIGNS OF CORROSION. THE COMMODITY WAS DRANO MAX GEL. CLASSIFIED AS UN1760 CORROSIVE LIQUID, N.O.S. (SODIUM HYDROXIDE, SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE), 8, PGIII. DG ADMIN INSTRUCTED THEM TO PLACE THE PACKAGE IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND TO HOLD THE SHIPMENT UNTIL FURTHER ADVISED.

column168: Cargo tank manhole cover was not secured or closed for transportation. Loading facility does not allow for driver/carrier to inspect manhole covers while on shipper premises. At aprox. 1800 on 10/02/2022 I(Virgil Hatton) was driving IWS truck#77. As part of my evening duties with Nova, I was at the Sumter Rail yard, and hooked up to tanker#9410. I pulled up to the east gate where the security guard and I inspected the exterior and sides of the tanker. We were not able to inspect the top of the tanker due to lack of fall! Protection equipment After leaving the east gate, I was enroute to the Sumter Giant Resource Recovery (GRR) plant. I approched the stop sign at South Housar Str, made a complete stop, went straight for approx. 1/2 mile and made a right turn onto Brooklny St. After approx. 1/2 mile, I came to another stop sign; made a complete stop and turned right onto Fulton St At approx. 1/8 mile, I turned left onto Industrial Rd. After going another approx. 1/8 mile, as I slowed down to make a complete stop in order to turn left into the GRR plant, I glanced in my driver side mirror and saw a surge of liquid dripping down the side of the tanker. I made the left tum and, watching the driver's side mirror, saw the dome lid on top the tanker open in an upright position. I immediately stopped my truck, got out, climbed up the ladder to the top of the tanker, then I closed and Latched the dome lid. I got back in my truck, proceeded through the security gate and parked my truck at the plant. I immediately notified Nova plant supervisor Jeff and Greg. They started Spill Response at this time. After they told me there was nothing more for me to do at this time, I unhooked Tanker#9410 from my truck. I left the GRR plant, and backtracked my route from GRR plant to the rail yard to look for evidence or a spill. There was none. I called Nova supervisor Jeff to inform him there was no spill. ///End of Statement///
column169: TO PREVENT AND ELIMINATE FUTURE OCCURANCE, IWS AND NOVA ARE NOW TRIPLE CHECKING THE MANHOLE COVERS AND VALVES FOR SECUREMENT SO THIS DOESN'T EVER HAPPEN AGAIN. MOTOR CARRIER EMPLOYEE/DRIVER IS NOW REQUIRED TO INSPECT MANHOLE COVERS AND VALVES BEFORE ACCEPTING SHIPMENTS FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: As Flight Attendant 4 and I were working the beverage cart serving beverages and snacks to the Main Cabin passengers, we were at Row 16 when I witnessed an explosion in Row 20. I heard a loud noise from the explosion and saw sparks flying, both black and white smoke quickly appeared and filled the entire cabin. I was on the forward part of the cart and ran up to the Forward Galley to inform Flight Attendant 1, that we had a safety alert and that there was an explosion of a battery of some sort and that the cabin was filling with smoke. I then ran back to the cart and took out the Fire Containment bag from the overhead bin above row 16. I handed Flight Attendant 4 the fire containment bag while the FA2, brought an insert to put the"Baby Bottle Warmer" in that exploded into the fire containment bag and to the AFT galley where FA4 cleared out a catering cart to put the fire containment bag in. The passenger, Mikaila Norwood, and her infant, had black charred on their faces, so we gave her water and napkins to wipe her face with and the baby's face. We notified the pilots what happened, and they were told to continue to DFW if the situation was under control. Mikaila Norwood, refused any medical attention, even though the nurse on board suggested we get an oxygen tank for the infant child to use. We turned the power ports off for the rest of the flight.· The customer had plugged the baby bottle warmer into the USB powerport between the seats before the incident occurred.
